. :thumbsup: to both @xergic and @jakelisby for this. This worked for me. You can also get the FXFormBaseCell sent back with the selector method. I'm using this to determine if my options were inline or not.
```
FXFormFieldAction: @"itemSelected:"

(void)itemSelected:(id)sender {
    // Option selected, navigate back automatically for user
    FXFormBaseCell baseCell = (FXFormBaseCell )sender;
    if (!baseCell.field.isInline) {
        [self.navigationController popViewControllerAnimated:YES];
    }
}
``
. Excellent, that works brilliantly! I didn't think it would be that trivial, thanks for the help.
. It's been a few months since I've worked with FXForms, so forgive me if I'm missing some details in my answer. I was able to validate input by adding anFXFormFieldActionto the field. You do this by assigning a selector string to the keyFXFormFieldAction` ("action"). I believe the action will be performed whenever the field is selected and when the first responder is resigned (user navigates out of the field)

Here is an example on validating a date code in the format MMYY.
When building your field...
// Don't forget the colon after the selector string so you can get the field in your method!
[fieldDict setValue:@"checkDateCodeRegEx:" forKey: FXFormFieldAction];
Now create the selector method. I put the method in the view controller that presented the form. From the FXForm README, "...the target is determined by cascading up the responder chain from the cell until an object is encountered that responds to it. That means that you could choose to implement this action method on the tableview, its superview, the view controller, the app delegate, or even the window."
```
- (void)checkDateCodeRegEx:(id)sender {
    FXFormTextFieldCell fieldCell = (FXFormTextFieldCell )sender;
    NSString *inputString = [NSString stringWithFormat:@"%@", fieldCell.field.value];
NSString *regex = @"^(0[1-9]|1[0-2])[0-9][0-9]$";  // MMYY
NSPredicate *regexTest = [NSPredicate predicateWithFormat:@"SELF MATCHES %@", regex];

if ([regexTest evaluateWithObject:inputString] || !inputString || [inputString isEqualToString:@""]) {
    fieldCell.textField.textColor = [UIColor blackColor];
} else {
    fieldCell.textField.textColor = [UIColor redColor];
}

}
```
This will simply evaluate what was inputed into that field, and then change the font color depending on if the input was determined to be invalid or valid.
. @confile You can do this by setting the textAlignment property of UITextView, which is a property of FXFormTextViewCell.
When setting the dictionary for the field that you want right aligned, set this key-value combination:
@"textView.textAlignment": @2
2 is the enumerated value for NSTextAlignmentRight.

. As far as the compiler is concerned, valideFirst and valideFirst: are two different methods. So you need to include a colon (:) at the end of your selector so that the correct method is invoked.
* Change the action selector to the following when you create the field...*
FXFormFieldAction:@"valideFirst:"
Then change the valideFirst method to the following...
- (void)valideFirst:(id)sender {
    FXFormDefaultCell *yourFieldCell = (FXFormDefaultCell *)sender;
    NSLog(@"Cell title = %@", yourFieldCell.field.title);
}
. Change the submitLoginForm selector to submitLoginForm: (add the colon). Then, in the view controller that presents your form implement the following method.
```
- (void)submitLoginForm:(id)sender {
    CustomButtonCell fieldCell = (CustomButtonCell )sender;
// Now you can access any of the CustomButtonCell properties
fieldCell.textField.textColor = [UIColor redColor];  // Assuming textfield is a property of CustomButtonCell

}
``
. You can set the field's property 'userInteractionEnabled' to NO/false. Assuming you're using the-fields` method to set up your form, it'd look something like this...
return @[ @{FXFormFieldKey: @"yourProperty",
          @"userInteractionEnabled": (/*Some check on if the field should be readonly*/) ? @NO : @YES,
           }];
